name: Lowell E Baier Hall/IU Maurer School of Law
description: Erected in 1956, the Law School Building's beautiful features house the Maurer School of Law and include the renowned Law Library, which recently tied with Harvard as the best in the nation. Former U.S. Supreme Court Chief Justice William Rehnquist and Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg have presided over mock trials in the school's Moot Court Room.

name: Bryan Hall
description: Called the Administration Building when it opened in 1936, Bryan Hall was renamed in 1957 after IU's tenth president, William Lowe Bryan. Top-level decisions affecting the university are made here daily. It is the home of the Office of the President and several administrative offices.

name: Franklin Hall
description: Home to various administrative offices such as the registrar and the bursar over the years, this English Gothic building was completed in 1908 to accommodate a growing library. Former IU President Bryan selected poet John Milton's words for the entrance: “A good book is the precious lifeblood of the master spirit.”  In 2016, a major renovation transformed Franklin Hall to the new home for the Media School including the latest advancements in technology.

name: Mathers Museum
description: The Mathers Museum of World Cultures is the only specialized anthropology museum in Indiana. The museum's collections consist of more than 40,000 photographs and 25,000 objects—ceramics, textiles, musical instruments, folk art, and costumes—representing cultures from around the world.

name: Glenn A. Black Laboratory of Archaeology
description: Named in honor of the first professional archaeologist in Indiana, the Glenn A. Black Laboratory of Archaeology was established in 1965 to promote Indiana’s rich archaeological heritage. The laboratory curates nearly 12,000 archaeological collections representing millions of artifacts. Many of them are on display in the public exhibit gallery.

name: La Casa / Latino Cultural Center
description: Established in 1973, La Casa fosters a sense of belonging for the local Latino community and promotes cultural awareness through its services, programs, and events, which include the monthly Colectiva Dinners and celebrations honoring National Hispanic Heritage Month, Dia de los Muertos, and Cesar Chavez.

name: Frances Morgan Swain Student Building
description: Listed on the National Register of Historic Places, the Student Building opened in 1906 and originally housed a parlor, auditorium, gymnasium, and a swimming pool. It is now home to the departments of Anthropology and Geography. Its clock tower chimes can be heard across campus every quarter hour.

name: Kirkwood Observatory
description: Built in 1900, the Kirkwood Observatory was named for former IU math professor Daniel Kirkwood, an astronomer who discovered the divisions of the asteroid belt known as the Kirkwood Gaps. On clear Wednesday evenings throughout the year, the observatory is open for public viewings through the main telescope.

name: Rose Well House
description: Donated in 1908, the open structure was named for its benefactor, Theodore Rose. It was designed in the shape of a Beta Theta Pi fraternity pin from materials from the old College Building. Legend says a female student isn't a true co-ed until she is kissed here at midnight.

name: Maxwell Hall
description: When built in 1890, the Romanesque Revival “Library Hall” was IU's first library. The stunning limestone building was renamed Maxwell Hall in 1894 to honor Dr. David H. Maxwell. Today it houses offices that focus on undergraduate education, such as University Division and the General Studies Degree Program.

name: McCalla School
description: The Margaret McCalla Elementary School is a brick Classical Revival building that was purchased by IU as studio space for Henry Radford School of Fine Arts sculpture students. Named for McCalla's last principal, Herschell Fuller, the Fuller Projects venue regularly hosts contemporary art shows.

The Hutton Honors College was dedicated in April 2009, shortly after its benefactor and namesake Edward L. Hutton passed away. This spacious home-away-from-home for honors students has a red oak–paneled library, a great room for distinguished speakers, and space for meetings and film screenings.
name: Honors College (Edward  L. Hutton Honors College)

description: The 500,000-square-foot Indiana Memorial Union is the second largest in America. It houses dining areas, snack shops, a coffeehouse, a three-story bookstore, a credit union, a 187-room hotel, a 400-seat theatre, a hair salon, a bowling alley, a billiards room, an arcade, and an eight-story student activities tower.
name: Indiana Memorial Union (Union Building)

description: Owen Hall and Wylie Hall were the first two buildings erected on the IU campus after the fire of 1883. Completed in 1885 in High Victorian Gothic style, the four-story hall is named for Richard Owen, the late IU professor of geology.
name: Owen Hall

description: Wylie Hall and Owen Hall were the first two buildings erected on the IU campus after the fire of 1883. The High Victorian Gothic–style building was dedicated in 1885 in honor of IU's first president, Andrew Wylie, and his cousin Theophilus, a professor of natural science and chemistry.
name: Wylie Hall

description: Completed in 1967, the Optometry Building offers on-site training for optometry students. The building contains classrooms, primary care exam rooms,  a pediatric/binocular vision clinic, a primary care clinic, a contact lens clinic, the Borish Center for Ophthalmic Research, and the full-service Atwater Eye Care Center and Eye Wear Center.
name: Optometry, School of

description: Dedicated in 2007, the 140,000-square-foot Simon Hall (MSB I) is the first of three IU multidisciplinary science buildings. This flagship research facility houses high-tech lab space for more than 220 researchers in the life sciences. MSB II opened in 2009, and MSB III is currently being planned.
name: Simon Hall (Multi-Disciplinary Sciences)

description: Built in 1931, the Chemistry Building boasts many IU campus firsts—it housed the first photocopy machine and the first CD-ROM player. It remains a cutting-edge facility with renowned laboratories. The famous “Sweetheart Tree” still grows inside the center of the building.
name: Chemistry

category: guard hut in HPER Parking Lot
name: 8th St Guard Hut (HPER)

description: Ernie Pyle Hall was completed in 1938 and renamed in 1954 to honor Pyle, the 1944 Pulitzer-prize winning World War II correspondent and IU student journalist. Students publish the Indiana Daily Student and Arbutus from its newsrooms and use its state-of-the-art technology for magazines, video documentaries, and investigative reports.
name: Ernie Pyle Hall

description: The Wildermuth Intramural Center opened in 1928 as the IU Fieldhouse and was home to the Hoosiers' 1940 and 1953 NCAA basketball championships, five Big Ten Conference titles, 20 All-American players, 17 All-Big Ten players, and three Big Ten Most Valuable Players. It is currently used for intramural sports.
name: Ora. L. Wildermuth Intramural Center (School of Public Health Complex)

description: Completed in 1956 to offer a quiet retreat for everyone on campus, the nondemoninational Beck Chapel is also a favorite location for small weddings and special occasions. IU First Lady Laurie Burns and IU President Michael McRobbie said their vows here in 2005.
name: Beck Chapel

description: Indiana stone carver Harry Easton created the limestone friezes on the entrance of the art deco–style Myers Hall, which opened in 1937 to house medical sciences. It is now the home of the Molecular Biology Institute, where researchers study advanced microscopy, DNA sequencing, X-ray crystallography, and plant genetics.
name: Myers Hall

description: Dedicated in 1956, Jordan Hall offers a showcase of inanimate and living biological exhibits. The preserved specimen cases, outdoor prairie plantings, and birds of Indiana paintings are available for public viewing, as are the public greenhouses—which hold unusual, exotic plants from every corner of the world.
name: Jordan Hall

description: Originally named Forest Hall when it opened in 1936, Goodbody Hall resides in the Wells Quadrangle. One of its distinctive features is a roof sculpture of Donald Duck wearing a mortar cap and glasses.
name: Goodbody Hall

description: Claiming the distinction of the largest academic building in the world when it opened in 1959, Ballantine Hall has a 10-story stature that is still the tallest on campus. It is also the most commonly known building—few IU students graduate without having a class here.
name: Ballantine Hall

description: The School of Public Health building supports the academic programs for the School of Public Health—Bloomington, and well as the programs offered by the Division of Recreational Sports. Indoor and outdoor sports facilities, the school library, and the Enberg Distance Learning Studio are among its exceptional resources.
name: School of Public Health (former HPER)

description: Originally the Business and Economics Building, Woodburn Hall was renamed to honor James Woodburn, IU professor of history from 1890 to 1924. Two panels of the famous mural "Social History of the State of Indiana” by Thomas Hart Benton are housed in its large lecture hall.
name: Woodburn Hall

description: The William Lowe and Charlotte Lowe Bryan House has been the home of every IU president, except Joseph Lee Sutton, since it was built in 1924. Yo-Yo Ma, Eleanor Roosevelt, and Robert Frost are among the famous people who have been presidents' guests here.
name: Bryan House
Social Research, Institute for / Center for Survey Research

description: Merrill Hall was dedicated in 1937 and renamed in 1989 after former Department of Music Head Barzille Merrill. The department became the School of Music in 1921. Merrill Hall houses the school's most historic performance space—Recital Hall—where world-renowned musicians have played for more than 65 years.
name: Merrill Hall (Music) / Music, Jacobs School of

description: Sycamore Hall was built in 1940 and is part of Wells Quadrangle. Made of Indiana limestone in the Collegiate Gothic style, it originally served as a female dormitory and is now home to the School of Nursing and the departments of Philosophy, Religious Studies, India Studies, and Latino Studies.
name: Sycamore Hall
East Studio Building (Jacobs School of Music)

description: The Sidney & Lois Eskenazi Museum of Art is ranked as a top-five American university art museum and holds an impressive collection that includes works by Claude Monet and Pablo Picasso. World-renowned architect I.M. Pei used no right angles in the construction of this unique building, which was completed in 1982.
name: Sidney and Lois Eskenazi Museum of Art

description: Since its dedication in 1960, the Lilly Library's holdings have grown to approximately  400,000 books, 100,000 pieces of sheet music, and 6.5 million manuscripts. Its rare collections include the Gutenberg bible, Shakespeare folios, John Ford's Oscar statue, and 30,000 Batman comics donated by IU alumnus Michael Uslan.
name: Lilly Library

description: Fine Arts boasts the region's best contemporary art space—the Grunwald Gallery—where shows are held regularly throughout the year. More than 320,000 slides are accessible through the Slide Library, and the Fine Arts Library contains more than 90,000 volumes.
name: Fine Arts, Henry Radford Hope School of

description: The Radio-Television Center  provides the surrounding area with local music and news as well as national programs from NPR and PBS. WFIU radio and WTIU television programs are broadcasted from the center, which also houses IU Radio and Television Services.
name: Radio-Television Center (WFIU and WTIU)

description: From Wilco to the Metropolitan Opera, the world's top performing acts have been entertaining audiences at the IU Auditorium for more than 70 years. Built in 1941 and renovated in 1999, the Auditorium has 3,154 seats, a 4,543 pipe Schantz organ, and a 3,700 square-foot stage.
name: Auditorium

description: The Lee Norvelle Theatre and Drama center provides workshops, directing and acting studios, and two performance spaces—the 443-seat Ruth N. Halls Theatre and the 236-seat Wells-Metz Theatre—which each host four shows annually that include Shakespearean productions, dance concerts, and small-cast plays.         Dating back to 1972, the Neal-Marshall Black Culture Center was renamed in 2002 to honor the first IU African American graduates. The center promotes the Black experience on campus and houses the African American Cultural Center Library, the African American Arts Institute, and the Office of Diversity Education.
name: Lee Norvelle Theatre and Drama Center/Marcellus Neal and Frances Marshall Black Culture Center

description: New arthouse releases, classics, and foreign-language films are among the more than 300 yearly screenings at the IU Cinema. The finest technology and luxurious period styling place this venue among the best in American university cinemas. Famous artists and directors visit to lecture here through the Jorgensen Guest Filmmaker Lecture Series.
name: IU Cinema

description: Built in 1972, the Musical Arts Center is the largest performance venue on campus and one of the grandest in the nation, with a 90'-by-60' stage that rivals New York's Metropolitan Opera House. It hosts the longest season of opera productions in the western hemisphere.
name: Musical Arts Center (MAC)
Music Library & Recital Center (Bess Meshulam Simon Music Library and Recital Center)

description: Overlooking a serene pond and several walking and bike paths, the Arboretum gazebo is a popular place for small concerts. It is surrounded by more than 450 trees and shrubs, hundreds of plant varieties, and a sprawling green space that is among students' favorites for relaxing and studying.
name: Arboretum Gazebo

description: Built in 1969, the Herman B Wells Library is the 13th largest university library in North America. Its Information Commons alone is the size of nearly six NCAA basketball courts. Don't believe the campus legend—the library isn't sinking. It rests on 94-foot-thick limestone bedrock.
name: Herman B Wells Library

description: The Leo R. Dowling International Center houses the Office of Overseas Study
name: International Center (Leo R. Dowling International Center)

description: The plan for the Wendell W. Wright Education Building was featured in Architectural Portfolio as an outstanding architectural design for education. Completed in 1993, the limestone building houses the Education Library and the state-of-the-art Center for Research on Learning and Technology.
name: Wendell W. Wright Education Building / Education, School of
Metz Carillon Tower
description: Built on the highest point of campus, this unique instrument room features a 61-bell carillon. The bells range in weight from 27 pounds to more than 3 tons, and each has as special inscription. The tower was presented to IU in 1970 by the Arthur R. Metz Foundation.

name: Hilltop Garden and Nature Center
description: Supported by donors and volunteers, Hilltop provides a central place for research and education in gardening and nature. In 1948, Hilltop initiated one of the first American youth gardening programs for grade-school children. Its community garden offers low-cost plots for citizens without garden access.

name: University Information Technology Services (Wrubel Computing Services)
Harry Gladstein Fieldhouse ( Indoor Track Facility)
Wilcox House
description: The “White House” was acquired by IU in 1981. The IU Foundation bought it for the use of the IU Student Foundation. In 1995, it was rededicated as the Wilcox House to honor Howard S. “Howdy” Wilcox, the founder of the IUSF and the Little 500 race.

name: Cecil W. Weathers Golf Team Center
1125 E. Atwater Ave.-Center for Latin American & Caribean Studies
Woodburn House (519 N. College Avenue)
description: IU President William Lowe Bryan, IU President and Chancellor Herman B Wells, and IU Professor James  Woodburn were former residents of the historical Woodburn House, which dates back to 1829. It has been a meeting place for IU students and faculty for more than a century.

name: Wylie House (307 E. Second Street)
description: Built in 1835 as the home of Andrew Wylie, IU's first president, this stately brick mansion is on the National Register of Historic Places and is now a museum recreating the early Wylie home. The grounds include a large garden with antique vegetable, flower, and herb varieties.

name: Showers City Hall-Monroe County Government Center
Residential Dining Services Food Stores (600 N. Rogers Street)

description: The Informatics East and Informatics West buildings and the new building that connects them form a 72,000-square-foot complex with the latest in modern classroom technology, befitting the first IT school of its kind. A fully wired courtyard allows students to plug in and power up between classes.
name: Informatics East

address: 611 N Fess Ave/674 E Cottage Grove Ave
name: Hillcrest Apartments

description: The DeVault Alumni Center is the central headquarters for all IU alumni. In addition to offices and meeting spaces for alumni, the IU Alumni Association, and the Student Alumni Association, the center has a 90-seat dining room and an outdoor plaza for entertaining.
name: Virgil T. DeVault Alumni Center

description: Home to the oldest continuing psychology laboratory in America, IU opened the Psychology Building in 1964. Its 20 laboratories support research in the Department of Psychological and Brain Sciences and include “wet labs” for organic research and an interior environment that can isolate sound and control outside stimuli.
name: Psychology
William J. Godfrey Graduate and Executive Education Center

description: The business school was renamed in 1997 after alumnus E.W. Kelley. In 2003,  the Kelley school added the Godfrey Graduate and Executive Education Center, which features elegant limestone and oak architecture, every imaginable technological advantage, and a two-story limestone walkway that connects to the original undergraduate building.
name: Hodge Hall (Kelley School of Business)
SPEA  / Public and Environmental Affairs, School of
Division of Residential Programs and Services

description: Herman B Wells purchased the house at the close of his tenure as IU president. He lived there during his 38 years as chancellor, and bequeathed the house to IU upon his death. The Wells House contains artifacts from his life and is used as a setting for celebrations.
name: Wells House

architects: Edward Larrabee Barnes & John M.Y. Lee
description: The 204,000-square-foot SRSC complex is one of the nation’s top recreational sports facilities. It offers multipurpose gyms, an indoor running track, a cycle-fit studio, free-weights, more than 400 pieces of exercise equipment—and courts for basketball, volleyball, tennis, racquetball, and squash. Registered students are automatically members.
name: Student Recreational Sports Center
